mage credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/Space Science Institute

The Cassini spacecraft takes an angled view toward Saturn, showing the southern reaches of the planet with the rings on a dramatic diagonal.

North on Saturn is up and rotated 16 degrees to the left. This view looks toward the southern, unilluminated side of the rings from about 14 degrees below the ringplane. The rings cast wide shadows on the planet's southern hemisphere. It was launched in 1997 and entered orbit in 2004, and is still in progress to this day.
